Barack Obama will be the fourth American president to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
American President Barack Obama will fly to Oslo in Norway to spend 26 hours there and be the fourth American president of history to receive the Nobel Peace Prize.
The $1.4 million diploma, medal and cheque will be awarded to him, among other things, for his exceptional efforts to strengthen global diplomacy and collaboration among nations.
The head of the White House and his wife Michelle will land in the morning in the Norwegian metropolis and will have a busy program.
He will first go to the Nobel Institute, where he will meet for the first time the five members of the Committee who chose him in October among 172 people and 33 organizations.
The presidential couple's planning then includes an interview with the King of Norway Harald V and Queen Sonja.
The visit will meet its summit in the afternoon at a solemn ceremony where Obama will receive the prestigious reward.
He will be the fourth President of the United States to receive it, but only the third will be awarded the prize in the Committee's own court.
The White House informed in advance that Obama would talk about the war in Afghanistan during the award.
The President does not want to avoid this issue because he is aware that he receives this prize by being a president who is currently leading a war in two countries.
He reinforced the war effort a few days ago by sending additional units to Afghanistan, which none of his critics would forget to stress.
At the ceremony, Obama will also receive a gold medal, a diploma and a check of ten million Swedish crowns (about 1.1 million Euros).
It intends to donate to charitable works, but it has not yet specifically decided which ones.
Her programme will then take her and her wife to a banquet including, in addition to the king and queen of Norway, the head of government and 250 other guests.
Obama was rather reluctant at first.
For example, he mentioned having the feeling that he did not deserve it fully.
He also repeated several times that it is not a price for himself, but for all those who defend the same values as him.
As soon as the announcement was announced, he stated that it would be an "invitation to act" for him.
