Czech discovery: a substance that works on HIV "endurant" viruses as well
A team of Czech and German scientists tests new combinations that can slow the proliferation of the HIV virus in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also acts on viruses that have already developed immunity to drugs.
This reality takes over in some cases the fact that the combination does not act as intensively on the current variants of the virus as well as some drugs already available.
It is not possible to cure AIDS at the moment.
However, the life of patients can be radically prolonged by a mixture of medicines that prevent the multiplication of the HIV virus in the body.
However, their consumption results in a series of side effects.
Moreover, the repression of this multiplication has the effect of developing what is called resistant viruses on which drugs no longer have an effect.
The work of experts from three institutions, the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, the VŠCHT in Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way to coping with the resistance of the virus.
They showed that substances called metalocarboranes act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of HIV virus.
Metalocarbons are a combination of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
This combination blocks the development of the virus in a different way from all medicines used so far and that is why they could overcome the problem of resistance.
The work of researchers leads them to discover new "improved" substances, based on their knowledge of molecular mechanics of their links to the virus's proteins.
Metalocarbons have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multiple-walled cages are formed by boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms and connected by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
A treacherous and resistant virus.
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is indispensable to the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV virus division caused by the HIV protease, there would be no mature infectious particles of the virus.
If HIV protease is stopped, the spread of the virus will also be stopped in the patient's body, explaining the researchers in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Czech Academy of Sciences.
In their work published in the journal of Medicinal Chemistry, scientists describe a series of combinations where two pairs of cages (see table) are connected by a short organic chain, which is then systematically modified.
A little weaker but more reliable.
The effectiveness of this series of HIV protease substances has been tested in test samples as well as on its resistant variants obtained from HIV-infected patients.
On the current version of the enzyme, the effect of metalocarborans is not as strong as on clinical drugs, however, it does not weaken on the resistant versions against which current drugs are often ineffective.
