The management revolution or the end of economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the governance of the great French companies, our fight for the development of economic intelligence will have been futile...
For more than ten years, the attitude of the management of large companies vis-à-vis their employees, recalls the position of the companies vis-à-vis consumers before the marketing revolution: it is about getting employees to adhere to "values" determined from above as it once was, to impose on consumers products thought of by factory technicians.
By putting the customer at the heart of the company, the marketing revolution has handed over market conquest strategies to the place... although the authoritarian temptation to impose disconnected products from customer preferences factors comes back regularly!
Demobilization of employees can lead to deadly demoralization.
Suicides in France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the emerging part of a much more general phenomenon that affects particularly managers.
This demobilization seriously undermines the development of all intellectual functions of the company, including R&D and, more importantly, economic intelligence.
Indeed, the EI "requires all stakeholders (...) a proactive approach and a forward-looking vision"; it requires a commitment on the part of employees that authoritarian management revenues are totally contrary.
That is why we call for a managerial revolution that would involve placing employees at the centre of the company's concerns in the same way as the client.
The relative usefulness of internal opinion investigations
Are internal opinion surveys – like the questionnaire submitted by Orange to its employees – going to stimulate this revolution in management practices?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
- First of all because I was able to see that, in the face of a new situation, every structure finally comes, after many deviations, to do priority... what it has always done.!
- Then, because of authoritarianism – one of the diseases of power – grows proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most leaders have a simplistic view of human behavior.
In large engineering schools, they have a mechanistic interpretation of psychology.
They adopt, by intellectual comfort, the old behaviorist theory, recently reactivated by the U.S. "nerosciences" and widely disseminated, in their own right, by the institutes of studies and the media.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the "leaves" of the engagement of executives, a recent investigation of Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr comforts leaders in a position of mechanistic governance, inadequate to today's world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the management revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern companies requires adopting a finalist view of human behaviour.
It consists of integrating, in any reason or practice of governance, a fundamental finding: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a means of realizing some of their dreams, ambitions, and projects.
Currently, only studies from the Reasonary Analysis adopt this concept of employees' motivations.
These studies have shown that they judge their business on the basis of a predetermined doxa that allows them, through their perceived image of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to carry out their life plans.
