75% of working mothers have had professional problems because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of young generations who want to be mothers.
This is reflected in the study "Féconity and professional career of women in Spain", carried out by the CSIC in collaboration with the Institute of Women.
The survey, carried out on 9,737 women aged 15 to 75, leaves no doubt: 75% of working mothers have seen their careers limited due to maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences regarding the beginning of life in couples and the number of children, whether or not women work and the type of employment occupied.
Those who do not have activity outside the home, work part-time or have an unstable job, get married earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier and have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, are reluctant to enter marriage and the first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women between 35 and 49 years of age with a fixed job have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after settling in a couple. This figure goes to 4.1 among those who work in the public sector."These data show that women with a stable job have needed more time in their lives to obtain it, which has led them to push away the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of employment exercised largely influences maternity, but less the starting date of common life," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that increases the gap in the age of women's marriage and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of training, the more they marry and have their first child late.
The difference is also maintained among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49 age group, those who conducted elementary and higher studies were mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 years on average.
"Another distinction is also found among women, depending on their level of study.
While those who have done elementary studies marry and have their first child before finding a stable job, those who have done intermediate or higher studies reverse this program and give priority to achieving stable work as a precondition for marriage and the arrival of a child," says Delgado.
