Emergency braking aid is now mandatory
As this has happened with the ABS brake anti-lock system and as it will happen with the ESP stability control, emergency brake support systems will be a mandatory element on European cars.
They are already mandatory on newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest of the vehicles a period of deficiency has been fixed until the end of February 2011.
The aim of the measure, imposed by the European Union, is to strengthen the protection of pedestrians, even though, by its way of action, it can also help to avoid many rear shocks.
The emergency brake assistant acts by increasing the pressure on the brakes in case of an emergency detected by the system thanks to the driver's kick.
But the latter does not always hold the pressure until the end.
According to a study conducted by the Bosch car component manufacturer, one third of the drivers involved in an accident had not been able to support the brake before the collision, and half of them had not taken full advantage of its strength.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, in return, requires the maximum brake system, reducing the distance the car needs to stop.
According to an EU study, if all cars were equipped with such elements, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided each year.
This reduction would be even more important with the popularization of these intelligent emergency braking systems: it is estimated that one in four fatalities with injured people would be avoided.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that, thanks to a radar or a camera, detects obstacles and prevents the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, it helps by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
